What if a chlorine gas line breaks?

The consequences of a chlorine gas line break depend on whether the line is under pressure or vacuum.  All lines at the Westminster Plant are under vacuum.  A vacuum line break would cause a loss of vacuum which would cause the vacuum regulator valves to close.

What if a chlorine container ruptures?

The quantity and rate of a chlorine release from a container rupture depends on whether there is a full or partial rupture.  For a partial rupture, it also depends on whether the rupture is in the vapor space or below the liquid level.  A worse case is a full rupture of a full container which would instantaneously release 2,000 lbs. of chlorine.  Listed below are some potential causes for rupture.

1) Failure of a defective container;
2) Failure due to a liquid-full container, with failure of  valve packing to leak                        (which could prevent the rupture by relieving the hydrostatic pressure);
3) Failure due to excessive physical shock;
4) Failure due to excessive heat or fire with simultaneous failure fusible plugs to                melt.

The facility has little control over a defective container that it does not own and will have to rely on the chlorine/sulfur dioxide supplier to ensure the integrity of the containers delivered to the facility.  The supplier for this facility will be responsible for periodically and carefully inspecting each container according to rigid quality control procedures.  All containers are registered with a specific serial number by the supplier which is stamped into the metal chime of each container.  In addition, containers are individually tagged and numbered so the operating and maintenance history of each container can be tracked.  Furthermore, visual inspections will be made of all containers delivered to the facility by facility employees, and containers which appear to be improperly maintained will be sent back to the supplier.
